messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path
- /consumer/subscribe

All HTTP methods acceptable?
- Yes â€” the @RequestMapping on the subscribe method does not specify a method, so it maps to any HTTP method.

Individual methods (based on the code)
- HEAD: true
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: true
- TRACE: true
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: true

Explanation
- The subscribe method is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/subscribe", produces = "text/event-stream") and there is no class-level @RequestMapping on NotificationsController, so the full path exposed by this handler is exactly "/consumer/subscribe".
- The @RequestMapping on that method does not set the method attribute (e.g. method = RequestMethod.GET), and by Spring MVC semantics a @RequestMapping without an explicit HTTP method accepts requests for any HTTP method. Therefore all HTTP methods listed above are accepted by this handler according to the source code.
- No other configuration files were provided that would prepend a base path or otherwise alter the route; the result above is derived solely from the controller source.
